==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hoarding
<hw>Hoard"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From OF.
<ets>hourd</ets>, <ets>hourt</ets>, barrier, palisade, of German or
Dutch origin; cf. D. <ets>horde</ets> hurdle, fence, G.
<ets>horde</ets>, <ets>h⟦uum⟧rde</ets>; akin to E. <ets>hurdle</ets>.
⟦root⟧16. See <er>Hurdle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>
<def>A screen of boards inclosing a house and materials while builders
are at work.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Posted on every dead wall and <qex>hoarding</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>London Graphic.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fence, barrier, or cover, inclosing, surrounding,
or concealing something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole arrangement was surrounded by a <qex>hoarding</qex>, the
space within which was divided into compartments by sheets of tin.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoared</ent>⟦br⟧
